				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">LocalH wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">ObOfftopic: Charles MacDonald? Of SMS and MD homebrew fame? On NESDev? Heresy, I say, <strong>heresy</strong>.</div><br /><br />Hey LocalH, good to see you here too!<br />If it shatters your belief system any further, I've written NES and SNES emulators in the past and have done a little R&amp;D on the SNES. But Sega is my true calling in life as you suspected. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Might I ask an offtopic question (feel free to reply via PM if you don't want to clutter this thread) - what exactly was your input on the iPhone Sonic 1 project? I noticed both you and "SpritesMind Community" got a special thanks.</div>
<br />
<br />I have not heard of the iPhone Sonic 1 project until now, so I assume they found my docs and/or emulators useful somehow. Thanks for bringing it to my attention.
<br />
<br />Clutter contribution:
<br />
<br />Maybe an easier solution to maintain a full range of colors would be to connect the composite video outputs of two PPUs to a 4066 mux, prior to amplification, and check when EXT1-0 of one of the PPUs was low, indicating a transparent pixel. Then the output of one or the other one would be enabled. This is what Sega has done in some of their multi-VDP setups with the RGB output.
<br />
<br />But it would only work if EXT1-0 were valid for the duration that the pixel data on the video output was displayed. I'm still unsure about that as they are tapped at an earlier point in the pixel output "pipeline", but perhaps the difference between the two is just a few tens of nanoseconds. Or not.
<br />
<br />In fact, there's no reason you couldn't chain together 3 or 4 PPUs this way, as long as the sync input and clock was common between them all. Any thoughts?</div>

